definitions: A person having a role or office next below that of principal; specifically a vice-principal of a university, school, or other educational institution.

notes.text: In early use with reference to the University of Aberdeen.

definitions: A stop pitched an octave below the 8-foot or 16-foot principal stop on an organ; the double open diapason.

notes.text: The stop is of 32-foot or 16-foot pitch if on the pedal, and of 16-foot pitch if on a manual (normally the Great Organ); it may also be a rank of stopped pipes, half the length of their sounding pitch.

definitions: An auxiliary rafter or principal brace. Compare "principal".

etymologies: early 17th century. From sub- + principal, originally after Middle French souz-principal

definitions: That is subordinate or secondary to that which is principal.
